Compare our biomass, the number of humans on this planet. To that of all the things that rely on, need, and consume carbon. And realize just how insignificant we truly are.

 @Karl Lieber  Much more then ice core data used to determine ice retreat around the world are the satellite images which indicate the undeniable reality that glaciers are retreating around the world.   

There have also been studies to determine the degree to which volcanoes on Antarctica have affected the retreat of glaciers.  Too much to go into here, but studies I looked at said volcanoes played a minor role in glacier melting.  Antarctica is a huge continent and studies have pointed out that glaciers are retreating primarily due to the warming waters underneath the glacier shelves especially in West Antarctica.  As those shelves break off the glaciers behind them accelerate to the ocean. 

Thwaites Glacier is one of five glaciers in west Antarctica that is most concerning because of the acceletated flow that has displayed in recent years.

 @Michael Deierhoi  
Does that mean you’re unaware of the crisis in ice core dating? It’s precisely how the history of glaciers has been told and the scientific method is being applied to show that history doesn’t look anything like what we’ve been told. The time period of satellite data on glaciers is meaningless, the equivalent of a single data point in terms of climate trends. 
There are conflicting claims about the effects of volcanoes on the few cleaving ice shelves, the few closest to recently discovered volcanoes, the few out of hundreds on the continent that are unaffected and no changes in trends, the few that the world’s foremost expert standing on the ice shelf he studied for decades says (I’m paraphrasing) “No, it’s the volcano, not the climate.” The “minor role” claims don’t even pass the smell test and certainly not the test of the scientific method.

