 @Dava Miller  Actually the ice packs around the world were stable through this last interglacial period called the Holocene.   But since the beginning of the industrial age humans have been adding an increasing amount of CO2 to the atmosphere to the point that CO2 and to a lesser degree other gases were retaining an increasing amount of heat in the atmosphere.  This became noticable about 30 years ago and has only became more so to the point that extreme weather events are becoming more frequent and more intense.   

The normal seasonal retreat of glaciers has accelerated dramatically to the point that the largest glaciers on Greenland and Antarctica are shedding ice at a record rate causing a rise in sea level.  High tides now flood some areas like Miami Beach and Norfolk Virginia.  

Hurricanes are larger and more powerful, flooding has worsened, as have the frequency of heat waves and drought.

